The carbon nanoparticle powder was dispersed in 32 organic solvents, covering a wide range of polarity (See Fig. 2
                        ). In every case, 4 mg of carbon nanoparticle powder were placed in clear glass vial (5 mL) with a screw cap before adding 4 mL of solvent for dilution (mass concentration = 1 mg/mL). The nanocarbon dispersion samples were then subjected to an ultrasonic bath at room temperature (25 °C) for 10 min. Ultrasound equipment: Unique®, model Ultracleaner 1400A, 40khz working frequency, Power 110 W. After the ultrasonic bath, the sample was left to rest for 120 h, after visual inspection. The sedimentation behavior was evaluated through visual observation, a widely recognized and practical method for assessing dispersion quality, which indirectly reflects the extent of agglomeration or flocculation [31,32]
                        . Following a 10-minute ultrasonication period, this study allowed the sample to settle for 120 h to enable sedimentation. Visual examination was then carried out, allowing sufficient time for sedimentation. Detailed observation data can be found in the supplementary file. Fig. 2 illustrates the various dispersion scenarios examined in this study, categorized as follows: transparent with sedimentation at the bottom (indicative of non-dispersible), translucent with sedimentation (indicative of partially dispersible), and opaque without sedimentation (indicative of dispersible).
